        <STIG_DATA>
          <VULN_ATTRIBUTE>Rule_Title</VULN_ATTRIBUTE>
          <ATTRIBUTE_DATA>Firefox private browsing must be disabled.</ATTRIBUTE_DATA>
        </STIG_DATA>
        <STIG_DATA>
          <VULN_ATTRIBUTE>Vuln_Discuss</VULN_ATTRIBUTE>
          <ATTRIBUTE_DATA>Private browsing allows the user to browse the internet without recording their browsing history/activity. From a forensics perspective, this is unacceptable. Best practice requires that browser history is retained.</ATTRIBUTE_DATA>
        </STIG_DATA>
        <STIG_DATA>
          <VULN_ATTRIBUTE>IA_Controls</VULN_ATTRIBUTE>
          <ATTRIBUTE_DATA></ATTRIBUTE_DATA>
        </STIG_DATA>
        <STIG_DATA>
          <VULN_ATTRIBUTE>Check_Content</VULN_ATTRIBUTE>
          <ATTRIBUTE_DATA>Type "about:policies" in the browser window.

If "DisablePrivateBrowsing" is not displayed under Policy Name or the Policy Value is not "true", this is a finding.</ATTRIBUTE_DATA>
        </STIG_DATA>
        <STIG_DATA>
          <VULN_ATTRIBUTE>Fix_Text</VULN_ATTRIBUTE>
          <ATTRIBUTE_DATA>Windows group policy:
1. Open the group policy editor tool with "gpedit.msc".
2. Navigate to Policy Path: Computer Configuration\Administrative Templates\Mozilla\Firefox
Policy Name: Disable Private Browsing
Policy State: Enabled

macOS "plist" file:
Add the following:
&lt;key&gt;DisablePrivateBrowsing&lt;/key&gt;
&lt;true/&gt;

Linux "policies.json" file:
Add the following in the policies section:
"DisablePrivateBrowsing": true</ATTRIBUTE_DATA>
        </STIG_DATA>
